Author::::DianaVreeland
DateTime::::2016-03-03T21:45:32Z
The clean air act was introduced in 1956 as people could see the pollution in the air - the soot and 'pea soupers' . It was clearly unhealthy and after rallies and mass demonstrations the act was passed. Now we can't see the pollution in the air as it is fine particulate - which passes straight to your bloodstream and causes heart disease, respiratory problems, etc. This pollution is even more toxic but the majority of the public remain in blissful ignorance because it's invisible. Awareness about air pollution is at the same stage smoking was in the 70's - to many, they say 'we all have to die of something'. It's in everyone's best interest to get this resolved. We do all use transport, but not in the same way. I am mocked because I am a higher rate tax payer and walk, cycle or use public transport. One of the advantages of living in the city is excellent public transport - if you are able bodied, you don't 'need' a car.



Author::::DianaVreeland
DateTime::::2016-03-03T21:17:12Z
Google 'induced demand' and 'traffic evaporation'. The data, going back to the 40's, demonstrates building more space for cars increases traffic. Similarly reducing road space reduces it. Freeways have also been successfully removed in Portland Oregon, Cheonggyecheon in Seoul and Milwaukee, Wisconsin, and replaced with residential areas, without the threatened choking of traffic.



