Author::::misterbaxter
DateTime::::2016-03-01T22:44:37Z
I live in Bristol, and I've commuted to work quickly and easily by bike on and off for about twenty-five years. During that time I've lived in various parts of the city wit commutes ranging from two miles to six miles each way, and I've worked in jobs ranging from workshops to smart-suit offices. Throughout the period I have had endless conversations with people who tell me that they'd love to cycle to work but can't, who turn out to live closer to their jobs than I do and are perfectly healthy people. Come to that, 11% of all car journeys are less than a mile; 29% are between a mile and two miles; and 60% of the remainder are less than five miles. Lots and lots of car journeys could be made by bike or on foot. People don't like the idea and they vote against anyone who tries to enforce it, as is their democratic right, but it's nevertheless silly to say that it's impossible to reduce the number of car journeys.



Author::::misterbaxter
DateTime::::2016-03-01T22:39:54Z
The point is not the organisation bringing the case, it's that the law actually requires the government to act on this and they are not. So lobby to change the law to allow more pollution, if you want, but don;t complain about laws being upheld by courts because that's pretty universally understood to be a good thing in a civilised country.



Author::::misterbaxter
DateTime::::2016-03-01T22:38:21Z
It's going to ask the court to consider whether the government is acting in accordance with the law; if not, the court will request that the government do so. We do actually have the rule of law in this country and the government is not above it.



Author::::misterbaxter
DateTime::::2016-03-01T22:37:13Z
My theory is that we're stuck in a faulty paradigm regarding vehicle options. We tend to think of the transport options as car; bike; train; bus; on foot; and then the various local tram / tube options specific to some cities. We can't move on from cars because electric versions of our current car models are slow and low-range compared to the fossil fuel versions; people don't like to pedal a bike up hills; it's too far to walk or they have baggage; the bus doesn't go where they want to go; and so we get in the car.But I'm just starting to see some new vehicle types emerging which might be a lot better. More and more people have electric bikes, which are great, but I'm also seeing a fair few people on electric trikes with a couple of children sitting on the rear seats and the shopping in a basket somewhere. Some of them look home-made, and some are custom built, but there seem to be a couple of brands emerging. I reckon that electric-assist cargo trikes ought to be huge. Mass produced, they could be under a thousand pounds new; they can go at 20mph which is as fast as cars get to go in the city anyway; parking is irrelevant and you don't need off-street parking to charge them, just a little bike space. Obviously the running cost is pennies. Loads of the groups of people whose cars are perceived to be a necessity (the elderly; people doing the weekly shop; people with children; tradesmen with tools; people with mobility problems) could actually get on just as well on one of these.The problem is British dignity, I guess, and a lack of investment. We need some good designers to find a way of making them look a bit more chunky and manly, or elegant and sleek, according to the various tastes of the public...



